<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-055-188  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 055 188.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Jan 15 1990 v36 n1792 p34(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DOD eyes purchasing changes to aid defense firms' profits. (USDepartment of Defense)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robertson, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Department of Defense (DOD) will consider acquisitionchanges to make defense business more profitable because'reputable' defense companies no longer want to take on governmentcontracts due to the low profit margin.andP;  Changes may includeincreasing progress payment rates, eliminating fixed pricedevelopment contracts, and increasing spending for independentresearch and development.andP;  Changes in the acquisition process andmanpower cuts will save $2.3 billion in the military budget in FY1991, says Defense Secretary Dick Cheney.andP;  The DOD will cut back42,000 jobs over the five years in the 500,000-strong acquisitionsworkforce.andP;  The cutback is to be accomplished largely throughemployee attrition.andP;  Other areas earmarked for cutbacks includethe Army Materiel Command, Air Force Systems Command, Air ForceLogistics Command, Air Force Communication Systems Command, andNavy laboratories.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Department of DefenseDefense ContractsProfit MarginGovernment ContractsMilitary.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>